40
00:04:25,800 --> 00:04:28,872
I'm not gonna tell you a pack of lies
to make me look good.

41
00:04:29,080 --> 00:04:31,116
I'm just gonna tell you what happened.

42
00:04:31,320 --> 00:04:33,197
My name is Yuri Orlov.

43
00:04:33,400 --> 00:04:36,278
When I was a boy,
my family came to America.

44
00:04:36,480 --> 00:04:38,311
But not all the way.

45
00:04:38,520 --> 00:04:41,557
Like most Ukrainians,
we congregated in Brighton Beach.

46
00:04:41,760 --> 00:04:43,910
It reminded us of the Black Sea.

47
00:04:44,120 --> 00:04:47,112
I soon realised we'd just
swapped one hell for another.

48
00:04:48,640 --> 00:04:52,189
Even in hell, an angel
sometimes makes an appearance.

49
00:04:52,400 --> 00:04:55,915
I'd worshipped Ava Fontaine
since I was ten years old.

50
00:04:56,120 --> 00:04:58,998
Of course, she didn't know I existed.

51
00:04:59,200 --> 00:05:02,078
I was startin' to think
she had a point.

52
00:05:04,800 --> 00:05:07,075
For the first 20-odd years of my life,

53
00:05:07,280 --> 00:05:10,875
Little Odessa was to me
what it is to the Q train:

54
00:05:11,080 --> 00:05:12,911
the end of the line.

55
00:05:14,560 --> 00:05:18,439
Oh, I did lie about my name.
It's not really Yuri Orlov.

56
00:05:18,640 --> 00:05:21,200
There've been few occasions
in the 20th century

57
00:05:21,400 --> 00:05:24,233
when it's been an advantage
to be a Jew, but in the '70s,

58
00:05:24,440 --> 00:05:27,989
to escape the Soviet Union,
our family pretended to be Jewish.

59
00:05:28,200 --> 00:05:30,760
Little about my life
has been kosher ever since.

60
00:05:30,960 --> 00:05:34,270
- How's it goin', brother?
- It's not.

61
00:05:34,480 --> 00:05:36,436
That's Vitaly, my younger brother.

62
00:05:36,640 --> 00:05:38,995
He was as lost as me,
he just didn't know it yet.

63
00:05:39,200 --> 00:05:42,078
Yuri. [Russian]
You late.

64
00:05:45,360 --> 00:05:48,158
My father took
his assumed identity to heart.

65
00:05:48,360 --> 00:05:50,078
He was more Jewish
than most Jews,

66
00:05:50,280 --> 00:05:52,396
which drove my Catholic mother crazy.

67
00:05:52,600 --> 00:05:56,673
How many times?
I can't eat shellfish. It's treyf.

68
00:05:56,880 --> 00:05:59,474
- You're not Jewish.
- I like it.

69
00:06:00,640 --> 00:06:05,919
I like the hat. It remind us
there is something above us.

70
00:06:06,720 --> 00:06:08,676
I like that.

71
00:06:10,400 --> 00:06:11,674
I'm going to temple.

72
00:06:11,880 --> 00:06:14,838
You're not going to temple.
You go more than the rabbi.

73
00:06:15,040 --> 00:06:16,155
[Russian]

74
00:06:16,720 --> 00:06:18,551
[mother speaks Russian]

75
00:06:18,760 --> 00:06:23,390
Yuri. Don't forget to check
the specials at The Palace.

76
00:06:24,360 --> 00:06:27,955
Growing up in Little Odessa,
murder was an everyday part of life.

77
00:06:28,160 --> 00:06:31,197
Russian mobsters had also migrated
from the Soviet Union,

78
00:06:31,400 --> 00:06:34,915
and, when they came to America,
their baggage came with them.

79
00:06:35,120 --> 00:06:36,394
[tyres screeching]

80
00:06:36,600 --> 00:06:39,751
Gangsters were always
getting whacked in my neighbourhood,

81
00:06:39,960 --> 00:06:41,916
but I'd never seen it
with my own eyes.

82
00:06:42,120 --> 00:06:44,714
I had this knack of showing up
five minutes before,

83
00:06:44,920 --> 00:06:48,037
or five minutes after.
Not that day.

84
00:06:48,240 --> 00:06:51,198
[# plaintive violin]

85
00:07:11,440 --> 00:07:15,274
It hit me. It couldn't have hit me
harder if I was the one who'd been shot.

86
00:07:15,480 --> 00:07:17,311
You go into the restaurant business

87
00:07:17,520 --> 00:07:20,751
because people
are always going to have to eat.

88
00:07:20,960 --> 00:07:22,439
That was the day I realised

89
00:07:22,640 --> 00:07:26,189
my destiny lay in fulfilling
another basic human need.

90
00:07:28,720 --> 00:07:31,792
The next Sabbath,
I went to temple with my father.

91
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:34,958
However, it wasn't God
I was tryin' to get close to.

92
00:07:35,160 --> 00:07:37,310
[father] Eli, my elder son, Yuri.

93
00:07:37,520 --> 00:07:43,470
My contact at synagogue landed me my
first Israeli-made Uzi sub-machine guns.

94
00:07:46,520 --> 00:07:49,990
The first time you sell a gun is a lot
like the first time you have sex.

95
00:07:50,200 --> 00:07:53,397
You have no idea what you're doing,
but it is exciting,

96
00:07:53,600 --> 00:07:57,752
and, one way or another,
it's over way too fast.

97
00:07:59,480 --> 00:08:00,959
Gentlemen.

98
00:08:01,160 --> 00:08:04,755
The new Uzi machine pistol,
big firepower in a small package.

99
00:08:04,960 --> 00:08:08,669
This baby uses 9-mm hollow points,
twenty 25-round extendable mags.

100
00:08:08,880 --> 00:08:12,839
Rear flip adjustable sights.
Excellent recoil reduction.

101
00:08:13,040 --> 00:08:16,077
Muzzle jump reduced 40%.
60% improved noise suppression.

102
00:08:16,280 --> 00:08:18,874
You could pump a mag
into me right now

103
00:08:19,080 --> 00:08:21,355
and never wake the guy
in the next room.

104
00:08:22,720 --> 00:08:26,918
Of course, that would eliminate
your opportunity for repeat business.

105
00:08:27,120 --> 00:08:30,078
I did have a natural instinct
for smuggling contraband.

106
00:08:30,280 --> 00:08:35,035
Fortunately, back then,
a video camera was as big as a bazooka.

107
00:08:38,600 --> 00:08:39,715
[sigh of relief]

108
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:44,594
I'd been running away
from violence my whole life,

109
00:08:44,800 --> 00:08:47,360
and I should have been
running towards it.

110
00:08:47,560 --> 00:08:48,959
It's in our nature.

111
00:08:49,160 --> 00:08:52,914
The earliest human skeletons
had spearheads in their ribcages.

112
00:08:53,120 --> 00:08:55,873
/# David Bowie: Young Americans]

113
00:09:04,040 --> 00:09:06,998
[father] Where have you been?
What if we had a customer?

114
00:09:07,200 --> 00:09:09,475
God bless America.

115
00:09:09,920 --> 00:09:11,876
[cash register rings]

116
00:09:22,360 --> 00:09:24,396
- Mm. Mm-hm.
- Yeah?

117
00:09:24,600 --> 00:09:27,478
- [choking noises]
- [Vitaly speaks Russian]

118
00:09:30,560 --> 00:09:34,348
"Beware of the dog"? You don't have
a dog. Are you tryin' to scare people?

119
00:09:34,560 --> 00:09:38,917
Nah, it's to scare me. Remind me
to beware of the dog in me.

120
00:09:39,120 --> 00:09:42,715
The dog that wants to fuck everything,
to fight and kill weaker dogs.

121
00:09:42,920 --> 00:09:46,071
I guess it's, uh, to remind me
to be more human.

122
00:09:46,280 --> 00:09:48,669
Isn't bein' a dog part of bein' human?

123
00:09:48,880 --> 00:09:52,077
What if that's the best part of you,
the dog part?

124
00:09:52,280 --> 00:09:55,431
What if you're really
just a two-legged dog?

125
00:09:57,080 --> 00:09:58,911
You need to see somebody.

126
00:09:59,120 --> 00:10:01,031
It stinks in here.

127
00:10:01,240 --> 00:10:03,834
I'd always wanted to do
something big with my life,

128
00:10:04,040 --> 00:10:05,598
I just didn't know what.

129
00:10:05,800 --> 00:10:08,519
Anyhow, I figured,
if I was going into the gun trade,

130
00:10:08,720 --> 00:10:10,233
I was goin' to aim high.

131
00:10:10,440 --> 00:10:14,718
[Yuri] Vitaly, stop fuckin' around,
I wanna talk to you.

132
00:10:14,920 --> 00:10:16,831
[seagulls]

133
00:10:17,040 --> 00:10:18,871
You read the newspapers, Vit?

134
00:10:19,080 --> 00:10:21,958
Newspaper? [scoffs]
It's always the same.

135
00:10:22,160 --> 00:10:25,436
You're right. Every day there's people
shootin' each other.

136
00:10:25,640 --> 00:10:27,153
Know what I do
when I see that?

137
00:10:27,360 --> 00:10:30,875
I look to see what guns they're using,
and I think "Why not my guns?"

138
00:10:31,080 --> 00:10:32,354
You opening a gun shop?

139
00:10:32,560 --> 00:10:35,233
Already more of those
in America than McDonald's.

140
00:10:35,440 --> 00:10:38,477
Even with all the gangsters here,
the margins are too low.

141
00:10:38,680 --> 00:10:41,831
- You've worked out the margins?
- Sure.

142
00:10:42,040 --> 00:10:43,314
Forget gang wars.

143
00:10:43,520 --> 00:10:47,229
The real money's in actual wars.
Between countries.

144
00:10:47,440 --> 00:10:50,671
Yuri, what the fuck
do you know about guns?

145
00:10:50,880 --> 00:10:53,314
I know which end I'd rather be on.

146
00:10:55,160 --> 00:10:58,596
I made the first sale.
We're already in business.

147
00:11:00,120 --> 00:11:02,554
Whoa... We?

148
00:11:02,760 --> 00:11:04,671
I need a partner.

149
00:11:08,160 --> 00:11:11,038
I don't know.
I don't know, Yuri. I don't know.

150
00:11:11,240 --> 00:11:13,993
Vitaly, I've tasted your borscht,
you're no chef.

151
00:11:14,200 --> 00:11:17,158
I can eat in the restaurant for free,
and I still don't.

152
00:11:17,360 --> 00:11:20,193
- Fuck you.
- We're doing nothing with our lives.

153
00:11:22,160 --> 00:11:24,196
I mean...

154
00:11:24,400 --> 00:11:26,152
This is shit. This is shit.

155
00:11:27,880 --> 00:11:30,348
That's true,

156
00:11:30,560 --> 00:11:33,597
but maybe doin' nothing's
better than doin' this.

157
00:11:36,680 --> 00:11:38,750
I need you.

158
00:11:39,160 --> 00:11:40,991
[Russian]

159
00:11:48,400 --> 00:11:50,595
/# Wagner: Ride of the Valkyries]

160
00:12:00,360 --> 00:12:01,634
[man] Sir, sir,

161
00:12:01,840 --> 00:12:05,628
may I interest you in the shoulder-fired
SA-7 surface-to-air missiles?

162
00:12:05,840 --> 00:12:09,389
The older model, not so effective
against modern military aircraft

163
00:12:09,600 --> 00:12:15,755
but deadly if used against a commercial
airliner. I'm giving them away at 850.

164
00:12:15,960 --> 00:12:18,793
It was the '80s,
and the Cold War was far from thawed.

165
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:21,389
Most deals
were government-to-government.

166
00:12:21,600 --> 00:12:25,036
It was a mostly private club,
with a lifetime club president.

167
00:12:25,240 --> 00:12:28,118
- That's him.
- Oh, the big shot?

168
00:12:28,320 --> 00:12:31,039
Simeon Weisz.
Angola, Mozambique.

169
00:12:31,240 --> 00:12:33,515
Those Exocet missiles in the Falklands.

170
00:12:33,720 --> 00:12:36,598
He was selling guns
before there was gunpowder.

171
00:12:36,800 --> 00:12:38,074
I'll be right back.

172
00:12:41,120 --> 00:12:44,157
Mr Weisz? Mr Weisz?

173
00:12:44,360 --> 00:12:46,715
It's OK, they're talking.

174
00:12:46,920 --> 00:12:48,911
- May I help?
- Yes. A mutual friend,

175
00:12:49,120 --> 00:12:52,749
Eli Kurtzman, from Brighton Beach,
said to contact you.

176
00:12:52,960 --> 00:12:56,350
I have a business proposal.
Perhaps we could discuss it.

177
00:12:56,560 --> 00:13:00,314
I don't think you and l
are in the same business. [laughs]

178
00:13:00,520 --> 00:13:02,636
You think I just sell guns, don't you?

179
00:13:02,840 --> 00:13:04,319
I don't. I take sides.

180
00:13:04,520 --> 00:13:07,910
But in the lran/lraq war,
you sold guns to both sides.

181
00:13:08,120 --> 00:13:12,671
Did you ever consider
that I wanted both sides to lose?

182
00:13:12,880 --> 00:13:16,555
Bullets change governments
far surer than votes.

183
00:13:16,760 --> 00:13:19,320
You're in the wrong place,
my young friend.

184
00:13:19,520 --> 00:13:21,476
This is no place for amateurs.

185
00:13:24,320 --> 00:13:26,515
[Russian]

186
00:13:26,720 --> 00:13:30,633
Curious how you revert to your native
tongue in moments of extreme anger.

187
00:13:30,840 --> 00:13:32,432
And ecstasy.

188
00:13:32,640 --> 00:13:34,471
[man and woman groaning]

189
00:13:34,680 --> 00:13:40,152
[Russian]

190
00:13:40,720 --> 00:13:42,711
[laughter, groaning]

191
00:13:44,240 --> 00:13:49,234
[Vitaly] Oh, you are beautiful.
What's your name again?

192
00:13:49,440 --> 00:13:51,670
[television in German]

193
00:13:54,720 --> 00:13:58,793
The only option for Vitaly and me
was under-the-counter gunrunning.

194
00:14:00,920 --> 00:14:05,277
I got my first break in Lebanon,
after the suicide bombing.

195
00:14:06,760 --> 00:14:09,399
But I wasn't the only
local kid making good.

196
00:14:10,560 --> 00:14:12,676
[distant gunfire]

197
00:14:12,880 --> 00:14:15,030
When the United States
leaves a war zone,

198
00:14:15,240 --> 00:14:17,913
they generally don't take
their munitions.

199
00:14:18,120 --> 00:14:21,430
It costs more to bring it back
than to buy new stock.

200
00:14:21,640 --> 00:14:23,232
[Yuri] So.

201
00:14:23,440 --> 00:14:24,793
We sell by the kilo.

202
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:27,958
They're second-hand weapons,
but they're still OK.

203
00:14:30,840 --> 00:14:33,400
- How many kilos would you like?
- 5,000.

204
00:14:33,600 --> 00:14:35,397
I had a flair for languages,

205
00:14:35,600 --> 00:14:37,875
but I soon discovered
that what talks best

206
00:14:38,080 --> 00:14:42,198
is dollars, dinars, drachmas, roubles,
rupees and pounds fuckin' sterling.

207
00:14:42,400 --> 00:14:45,073
Of course, the US Army
got a piece of the action.

208
00:14:45,280 --> 00:14:48,431
Army salaries were no better
in the '80s than they are today.

209
00:14:48,640 --> 00:14:51,438
Some of the brass,
like Lieutenant Colonel Southern,

210
00:14:51,640 --> 00:14:54,234
needed to raise money
for their own private wars.

211
00:14:54,440 --> 00:14:56,271
Good to make your acquaintance.

212
00:14:56,480 --> 00:15:00,598
This is bullshit money, Vit.
This is small fucking potatoes.

213
00:15:00,800 --> 00:15:03,997
- What, you wanna go more legit?
- No, more illegal.

214
00:15:04,200 --> 00:15:07,556
What I would give right now
for a plate of cabbage and potatoes.

215
00:15:08,960 --> 00:15:10,234
[gunfire]

216
00:15:33,920 --> 00:15:35,911
It's not our fight.

217
00:15:36,120 --> 00:15:37,872
Vit, come on.

218
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:40,558
Let's go. Come on.

219
00:15:51,400 --> 00:15:53,789
Selling guns
is like selling vacuum cleaners:

220
00:15:54,000 --> 00:15:56,560
you make calls,
pound the pavement, take orders.

221
00:15:56,760 --> 00:15:59,149
I was an equal-opportunity
merchant of death.

222
00:15:59,360 --> 00:16:01,749
I supplied every army
but the Salvation Army.

223
00:16:04,080 --> 00:16:07,197
I sold Israeli-made Uzis to Muslims.

224
00:16:07,400 --> 00:16:10,597
/# Flying Lizards:
Money (That's What I Want)]

225
00:16:12,680 --> 00:16:14,955
I sold communist-made bullets
to fascists.

226
00:16:15,160 --> 00:16:17,799
[Asian language]

227
00:16:31,160 --> 00:16:35,631
I even shipped cargo to Afghanistan when
they were fighting my fellow Soviets.

228
00:16:35,840 --> 00:16:37,751
I never sold to Osama bin Laden

229
00:16:37,960 --> 00:16:42,272
Not on any moral grounds. Back then,
he was always bouncing cheques.

230
00:16:45,320 --> 00:16:46,878
[gunfire]

231
00:16:51,320 --> 00:16:53,754
By the mid-'80s,
my weapons were represented

232
00:16:53,960 --> 00:16:56,952
in eight of the world's
top ten war zones.

233
00:16:59,320 --> 00:17:02,278
[ringing of cash register]

234
00:17:24,120 --> 00:17:26,270
There's no problem
leading a double life.

235
00:17:26,480 --> 00:17:29,278
It's the triple and quadruple lives
that'll get you.

236
00:17:29,480 --> 00:17:33,268
Back then I carried a French, British,
Israeli and Ukrainian passport,

237
00:17:33,480 --> 00:17:36,756
and a student visa for the US,
but that's another story.

238
00:17:36,960 --> 00:17:40,839
I also packed six different briefcases
depending on who I was that day

239
00:17:41,040 --> 00:17:43,190
and the region of the world
I was visiting.

240
00:17:48,080 --> 00:17:49,672
Without operations like mine,

241
00:17:49,880 --> 00:17:54,192
it would be impossible for certain
countries to conduct a respectable war.

242
00:17:54,400 --> 00:17:58,359
I was able to navigate around those
inconvenient little arms embargoes.

243
00:17:58,560 --> 00:18:00,676
There are three
basic types of arms deal:

244
00:18:00,880 --> 00:18:03,189
white, being legal;
black, being illegal;

245
00:18:03,400 --> 00:18:06,119
and my personal
favourite colour, grey.

246
00:18:06,320 --> 00:18:08,629
Sometimes I made
the deal so convoluted

247
00:18:08,840 --> 00:18:11,593
it was hard for me to work out
if they were on the level.

248
00:18:11,800 --> 00:18:14,394
To fool authorities,
I often spoke in code.

249
00:18:14,600 --> 00:18:17,637
Rocket-launchers were "mothers",
rockets "children",

250
00:18:17,840 --> 00:18:21,116
the AK-47 assault rifle
was the "Angel King".

251
00:18:21,320 --> 00:18:23,356
It's Yuri. [laughs]

252
00:18:23,560 --> 00:18:26,120
Yeah. Well, yeah, Raoul.

253
00:18:26,320 --> 00:18:30,438
Raoul, the Angel King
will arrive tomorrow. [laughs]

254
00:18:30,640 --> 00:18:32,596
Hallelujah to you too. All right.

255
00:18:32,800 --> 00:18:36,315
The point is, if I've done my job right,
an arms embargo should be

256
00:18:36,520 --> 00:18:39,432
- practically impossible to enforce.
- [telephone]

257
00:18:39,640 --> 00:18:41,153
What?

258
00:18:41,360 --> 00:18:44,113
OK, just slow the fuck down.

259
00:18:44,320 --> 00:18:46,550
I can't understand you. What?

260
00:18:46,760 --> 00:18:49,558
What do you mean, "tipped off'?
They know where we are?

261
00:18:49,760 --> 00:18:52,832
Where are they?
Well, how long have I got?

262
00:18:53,040 --> 00:18:55,634
"Not long"?
What does that mean? Shit.

263
00:18:55,840 --> 00:18:57,831
- Do we try to lose them?
- On this?

264
00:18:58,040 --> 00:19:00,952
- Yuri, we have to get off.
- No one's going anywhere.

265
00:19:01,160 --> 00:19:03,037
Slow. Dead slow. Buy me time.

266
00:19:03,240 --> 00:19:04,992
[bell rings]

267
00:19:06,200 --> 00:19:09,351
Yeah, it's Yuri.
Get that fuckin' rag down!

268
00:19:09,560 --> 00:19:13,189
I need another handle for this tub.
Something in our weight class.

269
00:19:13,400 --> 00:19:16,710
You! Over the side.
We're changing the name. Now!

270
00:19:18,280 --> 00:19:19,998
Yes, it's gotta check out!

271
00:19:20,200 --> 00:19:22,794
The way I look at it,
what's in a name?

272
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:24,274
You got a shorter name?

273
00:19:24,480 --> 00:19:27,278
I'd often changed the registration
of a ship or plane,

274
00:19:27,480 --> 00:19:29,948
but never at such short notice.

275
00:19:32,840 --> 00:19:35,149
Damn. They're hauling.

276
00:19:35,360 --> 00:19:39,990
What? "Kono"? How do you spell that?
K-O-N-O. OK, well, that's good.

277
00:19:40,200 --> 00:19:42,873
"Kono". K-O-N-O.

278
00:19:43,080 --> 00:19:47,471
What do we fly? Dutch? Got it.
Vit, get me a Dutch flag, will you?

279
00:19:57,520 --> 00:20:01,559
- Faster, or I'll send your arse in!
- Yuri, I don't have Dutch!

280
00:20:01,760 --> 00:20:03,273
- What?
- I've got Belgium.

281
00:20:03,480 --> 00:20:07,792
What use is that? He's painting a name
registered in the fucking Netherlands.

282
00:20:08,400 --> 00:20:10,197
- I've got a French flag.
- So?

283
00:20:10,400 --> 00:20:13,631
Turn it sideways, it's Dutch.

284
00:20:13,840 --> 00:20:16,718
[Yuri laughs]
That's why you're my brother.

285
00:20:38,400 --> 00:20:41,119
[Yuri] Good.
Everybody look innocent now.

286
00:20:50,480 --> 00:20:54,519
They say every man has his price,
but not every man gets it.

287
00:20:54,720 --> 00:20:57,439
Interpol agent Jack Valentine
couldn't be bought,

288
00:20:57,640 --> 00:20:59,392
at least not with money.

289
00:20:59,600 --> 00:21:02,160
For Jack, glory was the prize.

290
00:21:02,360 --> 00:21:04,590
Yeah, it's the Kono,
it's not the Kristol.

291
00:21:04,800 --> 00:21:06,756
Kono, K-O-N-O.

292
00:21:06,960 --> 00:21:12,080
- [man] It's clean,sir.
- Clean? It sure doesn't look clean.

293
00:21:12,280 --> 00:21:13,429
I'm gonna go aboard.

294
00:21:13,640 --> 00:21:16,996
Phone in a sighting
of the Kristol south of Aruba.

295
00:21:23,080 --> 00:21:25,640
Even when I was up
against an overzealous agent,

296
00:21:25,840 --> 00:21:29,071
I had a number of methods
for discouraging a search.

297
00:21:29,280 --> 00:21:32,795
I routinely mislabelled
my arms shipments "farm machinery",

298
00:21:33,000 --> 00:21:35,434
and I've yet to meet
the customs official

299
00:21:35,640 --> 00:21:38,757
who will open a container
marked "radioactive waste"

300
00:21:38,960 --> 00:21:40,916
to verify its contents.

301
00:21:41,120 --> 00:21:44,669
But my favourite is the unique
combination of week-old potatoes

302
00:21:44,880 --> 00:21:47,075
and tropical heat.

303
00:22:00,160 --> 00:22:02,720
It smells.

304
00:22:04,040 --> 00:22:06,349
Sir, a sighting of the Kristol,
due north.

305
00:22:06,560 --> 00:22:10,633
Most importantly, I kept a number
of intelligence people on the payroll

306
00:22:10,840 --> 00:22:13,991
to supply their colleagues
with counter-intelligence.

307
00:22:14,200 --> 00:22:15,553
Let's go.

308
00:22:26,480 --> 00:22:28,436
The second rule of gunrunning is,

309
00:22:28,640 --> 00:22:31,518
always ensure you have
a foolproof way to get paid,

310
00:22:31,720 --> 00:22:35,315
preferably in advance,
ideally to an off-shore account.

311
00:22:35,520 --> 00:22:37,670
That's why I chose customers carefully.

312
00:22:37,880 --> 00:22:40,394
Say what you like
about warlords and dictators,

313
00:22:40,600 --> 00:22:43,034
they have a highly developed
sense of order.

314
00:22:43,240 --> 00:22:45,151
They always pay their bills on time.

315
00:22:45,360 --> 00:22:46,315
[Spanish]

316
00:23:06,640 --> 00:23:07,629
Whoa, whoa, whoa.

317
00:23:17,560 --> 00:23:19,278
- What are you doing?
- Fuck you!

318
00:23:19,480 --> 00:23:20,435
Fuck you!

319
00:23:24,800 --> 00:23:27,234
Ah, ah... No, Vit!

320
00:23:30,040 --> 00:23:31,314
[Yuri] Shit.

321
00:23:31,520 --> 00:23:34,318
The first and most
important rule of gunrunning

322
00:23:34,520 --> 00:23:37,239
is never get shot
with your own merchandise.

323
00:23:38,040 --> 00:23:40,110
You OK?

324
00:23:40,320 --> 00:23:42,151
[sighs] I think so.

325
00:23:42,360 --> 00:23:45,193
- So what do we do now?
- Let's celebrate.

326
00:23:45,400 --> 00:23:47,960
/# Eric Clapton: Cocaine]

327
00:24:00,120 --> 00:24:01,519
Aah!

328
00:24:02,480 --> 00:24:03,435
[yelps]

329
00:24:08,600 --> 00:24:10,830
That narco-guerrilla
had his facts right.

330
00:24:11,040 --> 00:24:14,999
After shipping it stateside,
the return netted me a healthy profit.

331
00:24:15,200 --> 00:24:18,749
It would've been even better,
except one kilo never made it back.

332
00:24:18,960 --> 00:24:21,679
Vitaly? Vit?

333
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:29,197
To this day, I don't know
what Vitaly was running away from.

334
00:24:29,400 --> 00:24:31,914
Maybe just from Vitaly.

335
00:24:32,120 --> 00:24:35,999
I found him 12 days,
2000 miles and 1 50 grams later

336
00:24:36,200 --> 00:24:38,316
in a Bolivian boarding house.

337
00:24:41,920 --> 00:24:45,435
Of course, my dream girl
had gotten there before me.

338
00:24:51,520 --> 00:24:52,669
Vit?

339
00:25:02,480 --> 00:25:04,038
[Yuri] C'mon!

340
00:25:05,840 --> 00:25:08,149
[knocking]

341
00:25:18,440 --> 00:25:21,989
Ah, Yuri. It's my brother, Yuri.

342
00:25:23,200 --> 00:25:25,156
He's my big brother.

343
00:25:26,560 --> 00:25:29,632
- What the fuck is that?
- Ukraine.

344
00:25:29,840 --> 00:25:32,149
I was young, but I remember.

345
00:25:32,360 --> 00:25:34,954
Look. I...I start in Odessa, right,

346
00:25:35,160 --> 00:25:38,038
and then l... [gulps]
I work my way to the Crimean...

347
00:25:38,240 --> 00:25:41,073
You're gonna be dead before Kiev.
We're goin' home.

348
00:25:41,280 --> 00:25:44,511
- Come on.
- You fuck! You...fucking fuck!

349
00:25:44,720 --> 00:25:48,793
You fucking fuck!
What the fuck is your problem?

350
00:25:53,120 --> 00:25:54,599
[Vitaly grunts]

351
00:25:54,800 --> 00:25:57,678
[Yuri] Come on, Vit.

352
00:25:59,560 --> 00:26:04,475
- [Vitaly] It's so nice to be home.
- Yeah, we're gonna get you home. C'mon.

353
00:26:13,520 --> 00:26:16,830
[Yuri exhales deeply]
Get out of the car.

354
00:26:19,800 --> 00:26:23,031
Vitaly, I need you
to get out of the car.

355
00:26:24,240 --> 00:26:26,196
I promised our parents.

356
00:26:27,560 --> 00:26:29,755
- Please.
- You're gonna have a great time.

357
00:26:29,960 --> 00:26:32,758
It's a top place. Two Ford Models
checked in last week,

358
00:26:32,960 --> 00:26:35,520
that cute weathergirl's
been here since July...

359
00:26:35,720 --> 00:26:37,915
Please.

360
00:26:38,120 --> 00:26:40,076
Please, Yuri.

361
00:26:56,680 --> 00:26:58,671
You're a good brother.

362
00:27:00,960 --> 00:27:03,394
- You're a good brother, Yuri.
- OK. All right.

363
00:27:03,600 --> 00:27:06,160
- Good brother.
- All right, get out of the car.

364
00:27:06,360 --> 00:27:09,591
OK. Get out of the car.

365
00:27:16,640 --> 00:27:19,074
From then on,
I was a one-man operation.

366
00:27:19,280 --> 00:27:23,478
I never understood what separated the
recreation drug-user from the habitual,

367
00:27:23,680 --> 00:27:26,035
but, for the grace of God,
it could have been me

368
00:27:26,240 --> 00:27:28,595
snorting lines
as long as the Belt Parkway.

369
00:27:28,800 --> 00:27:32,509
However, I wasn't entirely free
of the grip of addiction myself.

370
00:27:32,720 --> 00:27:35,678
There she was again,
Ava Fontaine.

371
00:27:35,880 --> 00:27:38,633
In my neighbourhood,
they say the good get out.

372
00:27:38,840 --> 00:27:41,434
In our own ways,
we'd both conquered the world.

373
00:27:41,640 --> 00:27:44,598
/# Grace Jones: La Vie en Rose]

374
00:27:58,040 --> 00:28:02,670
You can't force someone to fall in love
with you, but you can improve your odds.

375
00:28:02,880 --> 00:28:05,872
It cost me 20 grand to book her
for a fake photo-shoot,

376
00:28:06,080 --> 00:28:08,958
another 12 to buy out the hotel.

377
00:28:49,720 --> 00:28:51,517
It's a popular hotel, huh?

378
00:28:55,520 --> 00:28:57,556
- Ava Fontaine.
- Yuri Orlov.

379
00:28:57,760 --> 00:29:00,115
- What brings you to St Barts?
- Photo-shoot.

380
00:29:00,320 --> 00:29:04,313
At least that was the plan. Guess
the photographer got stuck in Miami.

381
00:29:04,520 --> 00:29:07,637
Hurricane,
though there's nothing on the news.

382
00:29:07,840 --> 00:29:10,877
Those things can come out of nowhere.

383
00:29:11,600 --> 00:29:16,071
So the job's been cancelled, and
there's no flight back until Tuesday.

384
00:29:16,280 --> 00:29:19,670
You can hitch a ride with me
if you like. I'm leaving tomorrow.

385
00:29:19,880 --> 00:29:23,190
Meanwhile,
why don't I take your picture?

386
00:29:24,280 --> 00:29:25,429
In my experience,

387
00:29:25,640 --> 00:29:29,076
some of the most successful
relationships are based on lies.

388
00:29:29,280 --> 00:29:32,909
Since that's where they usually end up,
it's a logical place to start.

389
00:29:33,120 --> 00:29:37,636
Right there, right there.
Hold it. Oh, my God.

390
00:29:39,720 --> 00:29:42,518
I nearly went broke
convincing her I was anything but.

391
00:29:44,880 --> 00:29:48,270
I knew Ava was not a woman to be
seduced by a ride in a private jet,

392
00:29:48,480 --> 00:29:50,436
unless you owned the jet.

393
00:29:50,640 --> 00:29:53,393
- This is your plane?
- That is my name.

394
00:29:53,600 --> 00:29:54,874
Course I was lying.

395
00:29:55,080 --> 00:29:58,709
The plane was a rental, like the car
and even the suit I was standing in.

396
00:29:58,920 --> 00:30:01,878
At the last minute,
I bribed the crew for the paint job.

397
00:30:02,080 --> 00:30:07,234
Luckily, by he time we landed, Ava
wasn't looking anywhere but in my eyes.

398
00:30:07,440 --> 00:30:11,831
I had no idea.
I'm sorry I didn't recognise you.

399
00:30:12,040 --> 00:30:14,952
Don't apologise.
I put clothes on for a living.

400
00:30:15,160 --> 00:30:17,037
At least you're not taking them off.

401
00:30:17,240 --> 00:30:21,472
I would be if half the photographers
had their way. What about you?

402
00:30:21,680 --> 00:30:25,195
I'm in transport.
International air freight, mostly.

403
00:30:25,400 --> 00:30:27,152
Business is good.

404
00:30:28,160 --> 00:30:29,434
Where are you from?

405
00:30:29,640 --> 00:30:31,995
I was born in Ukraine,
but grew up in Brooklyn.

406
00:30:32,200 --> 00:30:33,394
- No.
- What, you too?

407
00:30:33,600 --> 00:30:35,750
Williamsburg.

408
00:30:38,560 --> 00:30:41,438
Well, here's to a hurricane.

409
00:30:41,640 --> 00:30:43,790
Without it, I never would have met you.

410
00:30:45,160 --> 00:30:47,594
This is no accident, is it, Yuri?

411
00:30:51,720 --> 00:30:54,188
It feels like...fate.

412
00:30:54,400 --> 00:30:56,072
I don't believe in fate.

413
00:30:57,320 --> 00:30:59,675
What do you believe in?

414
00:31:39,200 --> 00:31:42,590
- Is that a view, or is that a view?
- That's a view.

415
00:31:43,200 --> 00:31:45,350
[applause]

416
00:31:53,160 --> 00:31:55,116
[Yuri] Thank you. Thank you all.

417
00:31:55,360 --> 00:31:57,669
[murmuring voices, music]

418
00:31:58,880 --> 00:32:01,030
- [father] Mazel tov.
- Congratulations.

419
00:32:01,240 --> 00:32:02,673
Thanks.

420
00:32:04,840 --> 00:32:07,559
Always remember, son.
There is something above you.

421
00:32:07,760 --> 00:32:11,389
Sure, Dad.
A $40,000 crystal chandelier.

422
00:32:14,200 --> 00:32:17,033
Make yourselves at home. Go.

423
00:32:17,240 --> 00:32:19,629
- Go!
- [all laugh]

424
00:32:19,840 --> 00:32:23,150
/# Louis Armstrong:
A Kiss To Build A Dream On]

425
00:32:31,920 --> 00:32:34,309
I'm sorry. Today must be tough.

426
00:32:35,440 --> 00:32:38,876
Be nice to have a couple more guests
from my side of the family.

427
00:32:39,080 --> 00:32:42,993
- I'm sure they're watching right now.
- Thank you.

428
00:32:43,800 --> 00:32:47,349
But you don't believe that, Yuri.
Remember?

429
00:32:49,360 --> 00:32:53,717
I know you, Yuri.
I know you're not everything you seem.

430
00:32:54,960 --> 00:32:57,599
Don't worry,
I won't ask a lot of questions.

431
00:32:57,800 --> 00:33:00,234
I don't wanna hear you lie.

432
00:33:01,160 --> 00:33:04,311
You take risks. Just...

433
00:33:05,160 --> 00:33:07,833
...promise me you won't risk us.

434
00:33:08,040 --> 00:33:11,032
That's the trouble
with falling in love with a dream girl.

435
00:33:11,240 --> 00:33:13,800
They have a habit of becoming real.

436
00:33:18,480 --> 00:33:21,358
I've never been so glad to see Vitaly.

437
00:33:21,560 --> 00:33:24,870
You're fuckin' beautiful!

438
00:33:25,080 --> 00:33:29,517
Brother, brother, thank you so much
for giving me such a...beautiful sister.

439
00:33:29,720 --> 00:33:32,234
He was out of rehab,
and out of his mind.

440
00:33:32,440 --> 00:33:34,192
Dance, dance, we have to dance!

441
00:33:34,400 --> 00:33:36,675
- All right.
- It's a celebration. To Yuri!

442
00:33:36,880 --> 00:33:39,235
But for once, he rescued me.

443
00:33:42,400 --> 00:33:45,631
I was still living way beyond my means,
mortgaged to the hilt,

444
00:33:45,840 --> 00:33:47,990
using one credit card
to pay off another,

445
00:33:48,200 --> 00:33:50,794
anything to keep Ava
in the style to which she had,

446
00:33:51,000 --> 00:33:53,275
thanks largely to me,
become accustomed.

447
00:33:53,480 --> 00:33:57,393
- Ava. Ava, this is too much.
- Yuri likes to spoil you.

448
00:33:57,600 --> 00:34:00,160
Then suddenly,
all my Christmases came at once.

449
00:34:00,360 --> 00:34:02,715
[Ava] Nicki, you did it! Good boy!

450
00:34:02,920 --> 00:34:05,070
[laughs]
That's my grandson!

451
00:34:05,280 --> 00:34:07,191
Yuri, come see
what your son is doing!

452
00:34:07,400 --> 00:34:09,755
Whoever said it's better
to give than receive

453
00:34:09,960 --> 00:34:13,077
never got a Christmas present
like the one I got in 1991

454
00:34:13,280 --> 00:34:16,477
- from Mikhail Gorbachev.
- What the hell's the matter?

455
00:34:16,680 --> 00:34:18,398
- It's over!
- What's over?

456
00:34:18,600 --> 00:34:21,114
The Cold fuckin' War!
The Soviet fuckin' Union.

457
00:34:21,320 --> 00:34:24,118
Mikhail's saying "no mas"!
He's thrown in the towel!

458
00:34:24,320 --> 00:34:26,038
It's over!

459
00:34:29,000 --> 00:34:31,753
- Your son is walking.
- That's incredible, honey.

460
00:34:37,200 --> 00:34:39,350
At least they'll get religious freedom.

461
00:34:39,560 --> 00:34:42,028
Hm. Let's hope so.

462
00:34:42,240 --> 00:34:44,629
I think I'll go back for a visit.

463
00:34:44,840 --> 00:34:47,752
You stay in touch with Uncle Dmitri?

464
00:34:50,160 --> 00:34:52,355
I'm not a fool, Yuri.

465
00:34:53,960 --> 00:34:56,997
I don't think you're going
there just to sell Pepsi-Cola.

466
00:35:00,720 --> 00:35:03,075
Is this how you want to be remembered?

467
00:35:04,920 --> 00:35:08,879
I don't want to be remembered at all.
If I'm remembered, it means I'm dead.

468
00:35:09,080 --> 00:35:10,354
[door opening]

469
00:35:10,560 --> 00:35:13,279
Merry fuckin' Christmas!
[giggling]

470
00:35:13,480 --> 00:35:15,516
- Who is this, Vitaly?
- [woman laughs]

471
00:35:15,720 --> 00:35:19,508
- I'm Angel.
- Her name really is Angel.

472
00:35:19,720 --> 00:35:21,278
She's a fairy.

473
00:35:23,560 --> 00:35:27,075
Let's put her on top
of the Christmas tree! C'mon.

474
00:35:27,280 --> 00:35:28,838
[Vitaly] Whoa! C'mon.

475
00:35:32,120 --> 00:35:34,350
- [Vitaly] I love you.
- [Yuri] C'mon.

476
00:35:34,560 --> 00:35:37,836
- I love you all.
- [Nicki crying]

477
00:35:38,040 --> 00:35:39,996
Take this.

478
00:35:56,720 --> 00:35:58,472
I'm going back to Ukraine.

479
00:36:02,000 --> 00:36:03,956
I miss Odessa.

